Unified Terms & Conditions of Service Handbook (Generic)

SECTION 1 — INTRODUCTION
This handbook sets out the terms and conditions of service, benefits, and related employment matters for all employees (Executive and Non‑Executive). It supplements individual contracts of service and supersedes earlier handbooks of similar scope.

Management may update, revise, or add terms, conditions, or appendices from time to time. Such amendments will be communicated via official Human Resource circulars, which then form part of this handbook. Where interpretation is unclear, employees should consult the Human Resource Department. The contents are strictly confidential and intended solely for internal reference.

SECTION 2 — HUMAN RESOURCE POLICY
The organization regards employees who collaborate to achieve organizational objectives as key assets and representatives whose strength drives growth and success. In this spirit, the organization aims to:

·         Provide competitive compensation and benefits consistent with prevailing industry standards and trends.

·         Maintain a healthy, harmonious, and conducive work environment.

·         Engage personnel based on qualifications and experience.

·         Ensure effective implementation of human resources policies.

SECTION 3 — DEFINITIONS
3.1 Employee Categories

·         Executive: Employees in designated Executive salary grades (e.g., EG8–EG18) on regular, permanent employment.

·         Non‑Executive: Employees in designated Non‑Executive grades (see Appendix I for job grade examples).

3.2 Immediate Family Members

·         Includes legal spouse, children, parents, parents‑in‑law, brothers and sisters, grandparents, and legal guardians.

·         In cases of more than one legal wife, only one wife should be registered (Executive) / the first wife will be included (Non‑Executive).

3.3 Dependent Children

·         Children up to 18 years old, or up to 23 if studying. Exceptions apply where children are medically classified as disabled (mentally or physically) and unable to support themselves.

3.4 Gender and Number

·         Words in the masculine include the feminine; singular includes plural and vice versa.

3.5 Day

·         A continuous 24‑hour period from midnight to midnight, or any 24‑hour span measured from a given time point.

3.6 Leave Without Pay

·         Leave taken without compensation.

3.7 Misconduct

·         Any act or omission inconsistent with fulfilling expressed or implied conditions of the contract of service.

3.8 Inefficiency

·         Performance below organizational requirements (e.g., “Below Requirements” / “Far Below Requirements”) repeated over time.

3.9 Employer

·         Any party entering into a contract of service to employ another, including agents, managers, or factors acting for that party.

3.10 Contract of Service

·         Any agreement (oral/written; expressed/implied) under which one party employs another and the other agrees to serve.

3.11 Panel Doctor

·         Medical clinics/hospitals registered to provide medical attention and treatment.

3.12 Registered Medical Practitioner / Medical Officer

·         A practitioner registered under applicable medical laws (e.g., Medical Act 1971).

3.13 Shift Work

·         Work requiring continuous or continual operation by two or more shifts.

3.14 Public Statement

·         Statements or comments made to press or public, in lectures/speeches, or via sound/vision broadcasts.

3.15 Base Station

·         The normal workplace where an employee is permanently assigned and stationed.

3.16 Host Station

·         A workplace where an employee is assigned and stationed for project or temporary purposes.

SECTION 4 — CONDITIONS OF SERVICE
4.1 Working Hours

·         Monday–Friday: 8:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.

·         Lunch (Mon–Thu): 12:45 p.m. to 1:45 p.m.; Friday: 12:45 p.m. to 2:45 p.m.

4.2 Shift Work

·         Two 8‑hour shifts; or Three 8‑hour shifts; or Two 12‑hour shifts (as appropriate).

·         Minimum roster break: 16 hours before commencing a new rotation.

4.3 Probation

·         Executive: Up to 6 months; probationary performance reports at each 3‑month point.

·         Non‑Executive: Up to 3 months; extendable by a further 3 months at discretion.

4.4 Confirmation

·         Formal letter issued upon successful probation. If none at expiry, employee remains on probation.

4.5 Termination or Extension of Probation

·         Head of department recommends confirmation or termination at probation end.

·         Where performance/suitability is improvable, probation may be extended (Executive/Non‑Executive: up to 3 months) with areas for improvement communicated.

4.6 Notice of Termination During Probation

·         Two (2) weeks’ written notice by either party; reasons need not be stated.

4.7 Termination Notice After Confirmation

·         One (1) month notice or salary in lieu; accrued annual leave excluded unless pre‑approved to be taken within the notice period; written notice must state termination/last day.

4.8 Termination / Dismissal

·         Disciplinary terminations may result in dismissal after due enquiry.

·         Upon termination/dismissal, all organizational assets/documents must be surrendered.

·         Serious misconduct (or resignation to avoid such dismissal) yields no compensation.

4.9 Annual Performance Review / Performance & Development

·         Formal review and record of performance against objectives.

·         Action plans for the incoming year.

·         Counseling on strengths/weaknesses.

·         Role review against job requirements.

·         Career planning and training coordination.

·         Determination of salary increment and any ex‑gratia payments.

4.10 Age of Retirement

·         Retirement at 60 years of age.

4.11 Redundancy

·         May arise from restructuring leading to surplus roles.

·         Executive: Voluntary severance/retrenchment benefits at management/board discretion.

·         Non‑Executive: Severance benefits — <2 years: 10 days’ wages per year; 2–<5 years: 15 days’ wages per year; ≥5 years: 20 days’ wages per year.

4.12 Absence Without Leave or Reasonable Cause

·         Absence >48 hours or two consecutive working days without notifying/attempting to notify may trigger disciplinary action.

·         Registered letter sent; continued absence or no satisfactory explanation (including returned/undelivered after 7 days for Non‑Executive) deems the contract broken by the employee, leading to termination.

4.13 Overtime / Rest Day & Public Holidays

·         Overtime requested in advance; consent not unreasonably withheld.

·         Executive (RM4,000 or below): overtime per Employment Act (as amended).

·         Non‑Executive: overtime, rest day, and public holiday work per Employment Act (as amended).

4.14 On‑Call Duty

·         24‑hour, 7‑day on‑call rotations for operations/maintenance roles; device provision (pager/mobile) as appropriate.

4.15 Transferability

·         Employees may be moved between departments/locations and assigned additional duties.

SECTION 5 — SALARY ADMINISTRATION
5.1 Salary

·         Monthly base remuneration per organizational salary scales; due on the last calendar day (earlier payment may occur in organizational interest).

5.2 Annual Increment

·         Annual reviews occur; no fixed or guaranteed progression rate.

5.3 Upgrading & Promotion

·         Promotion increments: at least 5% of current base or sufficient to reach minimum/appropriate level in new grade.

5.4 Bonus

·         Non‑contractual; declared at discretion. Paid to confirmed employees based on satisfactory performance, prorated to confirmed service within the financial year.

SECTION 6 — LEAVE ENTITLEMENT
6.1 Rest Day

·         Office staff: Sunday. Operations/Maintenance (incl. Security for Non‑Executives): rostered as per management.

6.2 Public Holidays

·         All gazetted federal/state holidays are paid.

·         Ad‑hoc holidays recognized at management discretion.

·         If holiday falls on Sunday/rest day, next working day is paid replacement.

·         Additional annual leave credit when holiday falls on Saturday/off‑day: Executives joined from 2021 onwards (+1 day); Non‑Executives joined from 2020 onwards (+1 day).

6.3 Annual Leave

·         Granted for regular rest; encouraged to utilize annually; subject to exigencies of service.

·         Renews by calendar year on earn‑by basis; application via prescribed form to Head of Department; no employment while on leave.

·         Executive: <1 year pro‑rated; ≥1 year 21 days; hired before 2021: 25 days.

·         Non‑Executive: >1 year up to completion of 5th year: 14 days; on completion of 5 years: 18 days; hired before 2020: 21 days upon completion of 5 years; <1 year pro‑rated.

6.4 Carry Forward

·         Up to the lower of 50% entitlement or actual balance; excess forfeited. Must use within first 6 months; any remaining after July 1 forfeited.

6.5 Emergency Leave

·         For unforeseen domestic emergencies; offsets annual leave.

6.6 Compassionate Leave

·         Three (3) days (inclusive of rest/public holidays) upon death of immediate family.

6.7 Maternity Leave

·         Up to 98 calendar days per confinement; start date per medical practitioner. Miscarriage prior to 28 weeks is normal medical leave. No paid maternity leave if five or more surviving children at confinement.

6.8 Paternity Leave

·         Seven (7) consecutive working days from the birth date.

6.9 Marriage Leave

·         Three (3) working days; one occasion during service.

6.10 Unpaid Leave

·         Not normally granted to supplement annual leave except under special circumstances.

6.11 Medical Leave

·         Executive: up to 25 days (outpatient, not hospitalized); up to 60 days (hospitalized).

·         Non‑Executive: <2 years: 14 days; 2–<5 years: 18 days; ≥5 years: 22 days; hospitalized: 60 days.

·         If exceeded, deduct annual leave; if annual leave exhausted, treat as leave without pay.

·         Inform/attempt to inform management within 48 hours of illness‑related absence; failure is absence without reasonable excuse.

Extended Medical Leave for Specific Illnesses (panel doctor recommendation)

·         Executive: first 3 months full pay; next 3 months half pay; further 3 months without pay.

·         Non‑Executive: first 6 months full pay; next 6 months half pay; further 6 months without pay.

·         Termination on medical grounds may occur if return to acceptable duties is unlikely after unpaid period; procedures follow panel doctor recommendations.

6.12 Special Paid Leave

·         Examinations beneficial to work/future assignments.

·         Representing sports/cultural activities at organizational, state, or national level.

6.13 Transfer Leave

·         Two (2) paid days (incl. travel time) when transfer necessitates moving house/family.

6.14 Unrecorded Leave

·         Direct impact by natural disaster/material damage (e.g., flood, fire).

·         Court summons as witness or jury duty; documentation may be required.

6.15 Hajj Leave

·         Muslim employees with ≥5 years continuous service: 30 consecutive paid days, once during tenure. Annual/unpaid leave may be combined at discretion.

SECTION 7 — ALLOWANCES
7.1 Acting Allowance

·         Payable when covering higher‑grade duties for ≥20 consecutive calendar days (Executive) / ≥20 working days (Non‑Executive). Calculated as 10% of current salary or minimum of next higher grade (where available), whichever is higher.

7.2 Driving Licence Reimbursement (Non‑Executive)

·         Annual reimbursement of licence fees for drivers/dispatch riders.

7.3 Shift Allowance

·         Executive: Two 8‑hour cycle RM10 (second shift); Three 8‑hour cycle RM10 (second), RM15 (third); Two 12‑hour cycle RM20 (second).

·         Non‑Executive: Two 8‑hour cycle RM5 (second); Three 8‑hour cycle RM5 (second), RM10 (third); Two 12‑hour cycle RM15 (second).

7.4 On‑Call Allowance

·         Executive: RM50 per week; Non‑Executive: RM30 per week.

7.5 Subsistence / Meal Allowances for Extended Work

·         Executive: time‑off in lieu for weekend/public holiday assignments in construction/operations/maintenance/conversion; RM30 per day if working beyond 7:30 p.m. on normal working days.

·         Non‑Executive: RM12.50 per day if required to work beyond 7:30 p.m. on normal days/rest days/public holidays.

7.6 Temporary Assignment

·         Criteria: duration >1 month (<1 year typical), location >60 km from base, full‑time on‑site supervision throughout project.

·         Executive: RM1,700/month fixed; meal/day — RM5 breakfast, RM10 lunch, RM3 tea, RM12 dinner (total RM30); accommodation/day — RM25.

·         Non‑Executive: RM1,100/month fixed; meal/day — RM3 breakfast, RM7 lunch, RM2.50 tea, RM9 dinner (total RM21.50); accommodation/day — RM15.

7.7 Night Work Allowance

·         Executive: RM800/month (pro‑rated if <1 month); Non‑Executive: RM150/month (pro‑rated if <1 month).

SECTION 8 — GENERAL BENEFITS
8.1 Clinical Treatment

·         Employee, spouse, and dependent children (up to 18, or 23 if studying and not employed) eligible for free clinical treatment.

·         Coverage: general practitioner consultation for normal ailments; childhood immunisation; Hepatitis B; other preventive immunisation/injections per health authorities.

Exclusions (costs not borne)

·         Illness/injury due to proven fault/carelessness/indiscretion or hazardous sports participation/attendance.

·         Attempted suicide; unlawful acts; unjustifiable hazard exposure (except saving lives).

·         Provoked assault; use of non‑prescribed drugs; illegal abortion.

·         Artificial devices (e.g., limbs), spectacles/optician charges; cosmetic/plastic surgery.

·         Treatment by acupuncturists/homeopaths/traditional practitioners; contraceptive treatments; infertility treatment.

8.2 Hospitalization

·         Executive: entitled to first‑class public ward or equivalent private single room; if upgraded, employee pays difference; lower‑class option yields no compensation.

·         Non‑Executive: entitled to second‑class public ward or equivalent private four‑bed room; organization bears room/board per entitlement up to 60 days (employee); spouse/children up to RM40,000/year; specialist charges during hospitalization up to RM3,500/year.

8.3 Outpatient Specialist Treatment

·         Executive: eligible upon panel doctor recommendation.

·         Non‑Executive: eligible up to RM1,500/year upon panel doctor recommendation.

8.4 Maternity Charges

·         Executive: up to RM2,500 per confinement (excluding pre/post‑natal fees) for employee or spouse of male employee; max five surviving children; excess borne by employee.

·         Non‑Executive: up to RM1,500 per confinement (same conditions); excess borne by employee.

8.5 Dental Treatment

·         Non‑cosmetic dental care (extractions incl. surgical, fillings incl. root canal, X‑ray, scaling, gum treatment).

·         Executive annual limits: Married — RM1,500 employee + RM1,500 spouse/children; Single — RM1,500 employee.

·         Non‑Executive annual limits: Married — RM1,200 employee + RM1,200 spouse/children; Single — RM1,200 employee.

8.6 Medical Treatment — Overseas

·         Reimbursement for normal/emergency medical charges while on overseas business travel.

8.7 Company Vehicle (Executive)

·         Senior grades may be provided fully maintained vehicles or opt for monthly allowance; certain job‑tied positions may receive vehicles at management discretion.

8.8 Entertainment Claims (Executive)

·         Reasonable expenses for entertaining clients/dealers/visitors/officials reimburseable with prior approval and appropriate authorization.

8.9 Provident Fund

·         Contributions per statutory rates; employer may contribute above statutory rate.

8.10 Group Personal Insurance

·         24‑hour coverage for death or permanent total disablement by accident while employed; benefits up to 5 years of last drawn basic salary.

8.11 Professional Organization Membership (Executive)

·         Reimbursement for one entrance fee and annual subscription to one relevant professional body (recognized locally/overseas).

8.12 Corporate Club Membership (Executive)

·         May be extended to certain senior management or job‑tied positions.

8.13 Uniforms (Non‑Executive)

·         Supplied where duties expose employees to the public or as necessary; must be worn while on duty; remain organizational property and returned upon cessation of employment.

SECTION 9 — TRANSFERABILITY: ALLOWANCES / EXPENSES
Transfers outside a 100 km radius necessitating relocation entitle:

9.1 Travel Expenses

·         Executive: first‑class rail, appropriate air passage, or mileage for own vehicle.

·         Non‑Executive: second‑class rail or mileage for personal vehicle.

9.2 Settling‑In Allowance

·         Meals/lodging for employee, spouse, children up to 3 days with hotel receipts; private accommodation without receipts reimbursed up to: Executive — RM3,500 (Peninsular), RM4,500 (East); Non‑Executive — RM2,500 (Peninsular), RM3,500 (East). Excess costs are employee’s responsibility.

9.3 Relocation Allowance

·         25% of monthly salary, capped at RM2,000, paid once per location.

9.4 Transportation of Household & Personal Effects

·         For transfers beyond 50 km requiring family relocation: reimbursement up to RM2,500 against receipts (rail/road); storage/insurance costs (if applicable) covered.

SECTION 10 — TRAVEL
10.1 Business Travel

·         Organization meets reasonable costs so employees are not out‑of‑pocket; use fastest, most direct mode unless otherwise approved.

10.2 Travel Authorization (prior approval ≥3 days)

·         Local (Executive): appropriate authorities approve senior executives/department heads; heads approve staff in their departments.

·         Local (Non‑Executive): General Manager/Head of Department approve employees.

·         Overseas (all employees): approval by appropriate senior leadership.

10.3 Mode of Travel

·         Air bookings via department secretaries and approved agents; emergencies excepted.

·         Executive entitlements: Air — Business Class (senior grades, e.g., EG16+), Economy (EG15 and below); Train — First‑class with sleeping berth.

·         Non‑Executive entitlements: Air — Economy; Train — Second‑class with sleeping berth.

·         Personal vehicle: if air is more cost‑effective but employee drives, reimbursement limited to equivalent return airfare + tolls if mileage cost exceeds airfare; exceptions with approval for en‑route stoppages, lack of organizational transport, or odd‑hour urgent travel.

10.4 Mileage Claims

·         Car/4‑WD: RM0.85/km; Motorcycle: RM0.40/km.

·         Includes transfers/training/courses/seminars/meetings; excludes social/recreational activities.

·         Claims may be from base station/house to destination (whichever nearer).

·         Public transport claims require receipts; employees working on off/rest/public holidays may claim mileage.

10.5 Accommodation

·         Hotel: reimbursable single standard rooms; twin/double sharing encouraged when multiple employees travel together.

·         Private accommodation without receipts — Executive: Local Peninsular RM60/day; East RM70/day; Overseas Singapore/Brunei RM100/day; UK/Japan/USA/Middle East RM300/day; other countries RM150/day. Non‑Executive: Local Peninsular RM50/day; East RM60/day; Overseas Singapore/Brunei RM70/day; UK/Japan/USA/Middle East RM200/day; other countries RM100/day.

·         Non‑Executive hotel caps: Peninsular RM200/night; East RM200/night; Overseas actual as per receipt.

10.6 Meal Allowance

·         Without receipts — Executive (Local): 7:00 a.m.–7:00 p.m. RM25; 7:00 p.m.–7:00 a.m. RM25; Total RM50 (eligible if away >8 hours including night span).

·         Without receipts — Non‑Executive (Local): Peninsular: RM20 + RM20 = RM40; East: RM25 + RM25 = RM50.

·         Restrictions: no reimbursement if entertained by clients; no duplicate claims when one staff pays for others; alcoholic drinks excluded.

·         Overseas daily rates: see Appendix II/III.

10.7 Outfit Allowance (Overseas)

·         Executive: >6 months RM1,500; 1–<6 months RM1,125; up to 1 month RM900. Spouse (if >6 months): RM1,250; Children: RM250. Payable on receipts prior to departure; re‑claimable after 3 years.

·         Non‑Executive: >6 months RM750; 1–<6 months RM562.50; up to 1 month RM450. Spouse (if >6 months): RM625; Children: RM125. Payable on receipts prior to departure; re‑claimable after 3 years.

10.8 Travel Expenditure (Reimbursable)

·         Local: laundry (>2‑day stays), necessary transport where none provided, telecommunication/postage, airport tax (actual) and porterage, excess baggage up to 20 kg related to work.

·         Overseas: same as local plus out‑of‑pocket up to RM200 (airport tax actual, tips, porterage), family calls up to 5 minutes (arrival/departure), passport/visa for official duties only (not reimbursable if already possessed), excess baggage up to 20 kg related to work.

10.9 Reimbursement Procedure

·         Submit one claim per trip (outstation/overseas), inclusive of mileage entitlements.

SECTION 11 — CODE OF CONDUCT & DISCIPLINE
11.1 Expected Values & Conduct

·         Serve with good faith and fidelity; give undivided attention to duties.

·         Demonstrate cooperation, proactiveness/productivity; uphold work ethics, professionalism, esprit de corps.

·         Do not subordinate official duties to personal interests or use position for personal gain.

·         Do not act in ways that may bring disrepute or discredit.

·         Avoid inefficiency, dishonesty, insubordination, irresponsibility, criminal activities, or drug/poison abuse.

11.2 Publication of Books

·         No publications/writings based on official information without written permission and conditions.

11.3 Public Statements

·         No public statements/comments on work, policies, or decisions without authorization.

11.4 Participation in Media

·         No participation in advertisements/broadcasts in any media without prior written consent and conditions.

11.5 Conflict of Interest

·         No ownership (direct/indirect) of interests in entities listed as authorized contractors/suppliers; report any acquisition (including via immediate family) immediately in writing; organization will consult to prevent conflict.

·         If immediate family has interests and employee may deal with such entities, inform in writing prior to decisions/dealings; appropriate steps will be taken to prevent conflicts.

11.6 Outside Social & Political Activities

·         Voluntary public/social participation is encouraged but should not affect performance.

·         Report appointments/elections as an official to management; resign if standing for state/federal political elections.

11.7 Oath of Secrecy

·         No disclosure/use of confidential information during employment or within one (1) year after resignation unless required for duty.

·         No retention/copying of official documents without consent; return all documents upon termination.

11.8 Dress Code

·         Executives — Male: long‑sleeve shirts with neckties unless unsafe/impractical; corporate shirts permitted; T‑shirts, jeans, denim/leather not allowed. Female: smart, sober semi‑formal; T‑shirts, jeans, denim/leather, culottes, pantaloons not allowed; avoid revealing/outrageous or inappropriate attire (e.g., evening wear for discos/night clubs).

·         Non‑Executives — Male: smart, sober semi‑formal; jeans, denim/leather, T‑shirts, bright/floral/geometric prints, batik, bright tracksuits not permitted. Female: smart, sober semi‑formal; T‑shirts, jeans, denim/leather, culottes, pantaloons not allowed; avoid revealing/outrageous or inappropriate attire.

SECTION 12 — DISCIPLINARY PROCEDURES
12.1 Domestic Enquiry

·         Organization may conduct a domestic enquiry upon reported misconduct/inefficiency; suspension with/without pay may facilitate investigation.

·         Opportunity to be heard under the Law of Natural Justice; Board of Enquiry findings/recommendations are final.

12.2 Grounds for Disciplinary Action

·         Inefficiency, dishonesty, indiscipline, negligence, carelessness, insubordination, abuse of position/authority, criminal conviction, drug/poison abuse, breach of terms/conditions, breach of procedures/policies.

12.3 Disciplinary Actions

·         Verbal/written warning; suspension with/without pay; withholding/stopping/deferment of increment; stopping bonus (if declared); termination with appropriate notice; summary dismissal — as severity warrants.

12.4 Appeal

·         Right to appeal within fourteen (14) days from service of written disciplinary award.

SECTION 13 — EMPLOYEES’ SERVICE AGREEMENT
In consideration of employment, the undersigned employee undertakes and agrees to:

·         Perform entrusted duties truthfully, honestly, and diligently to the best of ability.

·         Observe and execute all directives, rules, regulations, and instructions by authorized officers acting for management.

·         Not engage in gainful activities/employment/business/dealings that may conflict with employment; obtain prior written consent where external engagements are contemplated.

·         Maintain confidentiality of transactions, accounts, information, dealings, and business affairs affecting the organization and its partners.

·         Carry out duties with undivided attention on all occasions.

·         Abide and comply with the organization’s Anti‑Bribery and Anti‑Corruption Policy and Framework.

This agreement is construed as an integral part of the prevailing Terms & Conditions of Service.

Signature (Employee)

Name of Witness (Print)

Signature of Witness

Date

Note: “Terms and Conditions of Service” refers to this handbook.


 

